Aliasing
Aliasing in SQL is the process of giving a temperory name to a table or column in a SELECT, FROM, WHERE clause.

Aliasing is often used to make it easier to reference a table or column in a query, especially when the actual name is long or difficult to read or write. It can also be used to 
specify a different name for a table or column in the output of a query.

Here is an example of using aliasing in a SELECT statement to rename the title column of a movies table to movie_title:

SELECT title AS movie_title FROM movies AS m;

Here is an example of a movies table with sample data:

id - title - year
1 - The Shawshank - 1994
2 - The Godfather - 1972
3 - The dark Knight - 2008

Here is the same table with an alias applied in a SELECT statement:

SELECT m.id, m.title AS movie_title, m.year FROM movies AS m;

id - movie_title - year
1 - The Shawshank - 1994
2 - The Godfather - 1978
3 - The Dark Knight - 2008

